SIMPLE: griffon
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Griffon
<hw>Grif"fon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>griffin</ets>, <ets>griffon</ets>,
<ets>griffoun</ets>, F. <ets>griffon</ets>, fr. L. <ets>gryphus</ets>,
equiv to <ets>gryps</ets>, Gr. <?/; -- so called because of the hooked
beak, and akin to <grk>grypo`s</grk> curved, hook-nosed.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Myth.)</fld> <def>A fabulous monster, half lion and
half eagle. It is often represented in Grecian and Roman works of
art.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A representation of this creature
as an heraldic charge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A species of large vulture
(<spn>Gyps fulvus</spn>) found in the mountainous parts of Southern
Europe, North Africa, and Asia Minor; -- called also
<altname>gripe</altname>, and <altname>grype</altname>. It is supposed
to be the ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>eagle</xex>⟦rdquo⟧ of the Bible. The
<stype>bearded griffin</stype> is the <stype>lammergeir</stype>.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>gryphon</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An English early apple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 651 --></p>

<p><ent>Griffon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Griffon
<hw>Grif"fon</hw> <pr>(gr⟦icr⟧f"f⟦ocr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F.]</ety> <def>One of a European breed of rough-coated dogs,
somewhat taller than the setter and of a grizzly liver color. They are
used in hunting game birds. The <styp><ecol><b>Brussels
griffon</b></ecol></styp> is a very small, wiry-coated, short-nosed pet
dog of Belgian origin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grig</ent>⟦br⟧
